               <head>Tsemaḥ Daṿid by Yūḥanna Dāʾūd</head>
               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85045096 lccn.loc.gov/sh85134665">
                  <summary>An ethico-religious work in Judeo-Persian.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="jpr" otherLangs="he" />
                  <msItem>
                     <locus from="1v" to="188v" />
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="he" key="viaf_97488913 http://viaf.org/viaf/97488913">יוחנה דאוד</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="en" key="viaf_97488913 http://viaf.org/viaf/97488913">Ben David Dawud, Yuhanna Mirza, 1885-1969</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="he">צמח דוד</title>
                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Tsemaḥ Daṿid</title>
                     <incipit />
                     <note>
                        <p>With numberous Hebrew insertions.</p>
                        <p>English note on back pastedown: '"The Branch of David": An
									original autograph manuscript written in Judaeo-Persian. on 374
									pages, 12 lines to a page, gilt-edge, 11 3/4 in. by 9 1/2 in.,
									bound in olive green morocco, with gold standard floral
									decorations. Entirely prepared to be published in a facsimile
									edition. Contents: The result of forty years of Biblical study,
									and research work, with many passages from the Bible, and
									restatement of certain ritual truths, so that they might find
									deeper root in the writer's mind and heart, as well as in those
									of others. "Deep calleth unto deep!" Y. Dawud.' </p>
                        <p>Yuhanna Dawud, known as Yohanan ben David in Hebrew and John
									David in English; a traditional Jew from a religious background;
									collected Persian works of art and Islamic treasures from his
									boyhood; Professor of Oriental Art and Literature; oriental
									translator; Curator of the Department of Islamic Art, British
									Museum; died London, 1969. </p>
                        <p>Autograph.</p>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
